# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australia-national-australian-rules-football-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The **1908 Melbourne Carnival** was the inaugural Australian National Football Carnival, an Australian football interstate competition, held in Melbourne in August 1908.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] It was known at the time as the **Jubilee Australasian Football Carnival** because it was designed to commemorate 50 years of Australian football.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] It was the first time in which all Australian states and New Zealand had competed together in the sport.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The winning team was presented with a silk pennant; and each member of the winning team received a gold championship medal.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Although the 29 August final between Victoria and Western Australia was played in front of something like 15,000 spectators, it is certain that the crowd would have been considerably larger if it had not also been the first day of the American Fleet's eight-day visit to Melbourne.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The official opening was conducted by Sir Thomas Gibson-Carmichael, the Governor of Victoria, at 3:00 pm on Wednesday 19 August 1908, in the interval between the first and second matches of the carnival (the first match started at 1:15 pm, the second at 3:30 pm).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The crowd of 7,000+ was in an excited mood: in the first match, New Zealand had come back from a 26-point half-time deficit to win by a single point.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The seven participating teams, with each player in their team uniforms, lined up and formed a hollow square.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The official party, the Governor of Victoria, accompanied by his private secretary, Victor Albert Nelson Hood (1862–1929), Sir Thomas Bent, Premier of Victoria, H.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Harrison, Australian Rules administrative pioneer (then 71 years old), Mr.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] "Ernie" Wilson, the first secretary of the Collingwood Football Club in the VFL, and secretary of the VFL from 1897-1929, and Mr.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Nash, president of the New South Wales Australian Football League, were each introduced to the captain of each team and shook hands.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The second match, played immediately after the opening ceremony, was nowhere near as exciting: Tasmania beat Queensland by 140 points.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Team photographs of all of the competing teams were published in the Melbourne *Punch*, and the Melbourne *Leader*.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Gluyas, Bert Renfrey (Vice-Captain), and Algy Millhouse from the Barrier, and G.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] McConechy, Ralph Robertson (Captain), T.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Watson from Hay, O'Keefe from Narrandera, plus James Greer and W.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the New South Wales team trained at the St Kilda Cricket Ground.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Paull (Wellington), George Dempster, H.L.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Ross (Christchurch), with emergencies, Burns, Welch, and L.A.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the New Zealand team trained at the Richmond Cricket Ground and was coached by Richmond's Dick Condon.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] This was the only time in the history of Australian rules "interstate" football matches that a team from New Zealand participated.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] It was anticipated that, immediately following the carnival, and before returning to New Zealand, the New Zealand team would play matches in Adelaide, Ballarat, Bendigo, Geelong, Sydney, Brisbane, and Newcastle.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The New Zealand team played a match, in Adelaide, on 1 September 1908 (Eight Hours Day), before the Governor, George Le Hunte, on a very wet ground (in several places the water was inches deep).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The match was not as one-sided as the final scores indicate: the score at quarter time was South Australia 4.5 (29) to New Zealand 0.1 (1).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] In the process of the day, the New Zealand team performed two hakas, one before the match commenced, the other before the second half began.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Greenwood, and Jack Keir (Locomotives), W.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Hopkins (Wynnum), Ralph McKellar (captain), H.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] "Bas" Bolton was a later addition to the team.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the Queensland team was coached by Jack Worrall, and trained at the Carlton Cricket Ground.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The selected team was; Charles George Gordon Gwynne, Ernie Johns, Jack Tredrea, Jack Chamberlain, Richard Townsend, Sinclair Dickson, Alfred Roy Le Messurier, Edward M.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Hewitt, Stewart Geddes (vice captain), George Wallace, Jack Mack, Tom Leahy, James Tierney, John Albert "Alby" Bahr (captain), Jack Woollard.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the South Australian team trained at the East Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The captain of Tasmania was Bruce Carter.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] The squad originally selected was: from the **South**: Roy Bailey (half back), P.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Orpwood (back), Walter Burrell (following and back), L.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Bridges (wing), Weller Arnold (centre), C.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Forster (rover and half-forward); from the **North**: Algy Tynan (full back), A.J.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Thomson (back), Charlie Searl (wing), Hastings Woolley (half-back and follower),Joe Littler (forward), Viv Valentine (forward); from **North-West Coast**: B.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Mahoney (follower); from **West Coast**: A.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Trotter (centre and forward), George McLeod (forward and follower).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Appleby (North-West), first back and follower; Norman F Pannam (North West), first forward and second follower; L.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Norman (North), rover and third forward; A.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Filgate (North-West), full back and wing.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the Tasmanian team, coached by Jack Gardiner and Dick Gibson, trained at the South Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Before the first match was played, it was noted that six of the possible "Victorian" players, Barclay Bailes, Bert Franks, Bill Goddard (South Melbourne), Harvey Kelly, Paddy Shea, and Phonse Wood had all played their first senior football in Western Australia.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] "Snob" Polglaise, Charles Tyson, Joe O'Dea.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] During the carnival, the Western Australian team trained at the Fitzroy Cricket Ground.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] All of the matches were played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Because Tasmania was beaten by South Australia, Victoria was the only remaining undefeated team.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1908-melbourne-carnival] Therefore, it was crowned the champions without the need for a Grand Final.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] The final was contested by Cork of Munster and Meath of Leinster, with Meath winning by 1–9 to 0–9.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] The All-Ireland SFC final between Cork and Meath was a unique occasion, as it was the first-ever championship meeting between the two teams.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] Cork were appearing in their first final in over a decade, while Meath were lining out in their second successive All-Ireland SFC decider.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] The first half was a dour, tense affair riddled with mistakes.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] Cork surged ahead into a three-point lead, while Meath only registered one point in the first half after being held scoreless for 27 minutes.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] In the second half, Meath were a transformed team.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] In his column in *The Irish Times*, Paddy Downey wrote: "Their second half transformation was so unexpected that it seems incredible.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] Nevertheless, it was a rally which for grit and guts and spirit surpassed anything I have seen in a final." Six minutes after the restart, Terry Kearns slipped unnoticed behind the Cork backline to punch Matt Kerrigan's centre to the net from 5 yards out.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] Their last-minute goal chance was pulled back because Con O'Sullivan's short free to Flor Hayes was deemed too short by the referee.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] Meath's All-Ireland SFC victory was their first since 1954.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] The win gave them their third title over all and put them joint eighth on the all-time roll of honour, along with Mayo, Louth and Cork.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] Peter McDermott of Meath, also known as "the man in the cap" and a winner of All-Ireland SFC medals with the team in 1949 and 1954, was coach of the 1967 winning team.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] Cork's defeat was their third at this stage since their last All-Ireland SFC victory in 1945.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] They previously lost All-Ireland SFC finals in 1956 and 1957.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] Meath subsequently toured Australia for some early examples of international rules football.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/1967-all-ireland-senior-football-championship-final] Meath played five Australian state sides and won them all, producing a combined score of 26-43 to 3-29.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] The team chairman is former Formula One world champion Alan Jones, backed by general manager and former NASCAR driver Peter Nolan.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] The seat is owned by Formula One talent-spotter come principal engineer Alan Docking through his eponymous racing team organisation.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] Will Power was the team's driver for the opening round at Brands Hatch, scoring a fourth place in the Sprint Race and a second in the Main Race, beaten only by Nelson Piquet Jr. who dominated the weekend.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] Power amassed 16 points for these two results; however, he had already signed for Champ Car's Team Australia and made no further appearance in A1GP.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] His replacement was seat owner Jones' son Christian Jones, who did not fare so well; round two in Germany provided no points and a best finish of fourteenth place.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] The uncompetitive Jones was replaced with Will Davison for round three in Portugal, and despite a qualifying performance of 18th place and a first-lap retirement in the Sprint Race, secured sixth place and five points in the Main Race.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] Davison was maintained for the home round at Eastern Creek Raceway, and again provided a sixth-place Main Race result.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] Davison consistently scored better in the Main Race in his drives, securing a one-point tenth place in the UAE round, although retiring from the main race in Durban.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] Contract obligations again caused a driver change when Davison switched to V8 Supercars; Australia's fourth driver of the season was Marcus Marshall, who scored the team's first podium since the opening round with a third-place finish in Indonesia.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] He also moved into V8 Supercars however, and the driver's seat reverted to Christian Jones, who was again uncompetitive.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] The seat for the last two rounds was awarded to Ryan Briscoe, who matched Power and Marshall's podium feat in the final round in China, with a main race third-place finish.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] In total, Australia's best results were a second place and two third places, for a total of 51 points and 13th place in the first-ever A1GP championship.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] Although Team Australia managed to secure three podium finishes during the 2006-07 season, they still finished the championship in 13th position with 25 points.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] Team Australia finished the 2007–08 season in 17th position, but did manage to score points in both the Sprint and Feature races of their home race.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] In the 2008–09 season, Team Australia scored their first ever fastest lap in the final race of the season, however just narrowly missed out on beating New Zealand in the final standings, finishing 8th.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/a1-team-australia] (key), "spr" indicates the Sprint Race, "fea" indicates the Feature Race.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] Cooney attended Flagstaff Hill R-7 Schools, Blackwood High School and later Aberfoyle Park High School and played for the Flagstaff Hill Football Club.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] Cooney was recruited from West Adelaide in the SANFL to the Western Bulldogs with the number-one pick in the 2003 National Draft as a priority pick.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] Cooney was noted as a pacey player who could kick goals on the run from outside the 50-metre arc as well as snap kicks near the goal posts.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] Cooney debuted in Round 1 2004 against the West Coast Eagles, where he recorded 8 disposals and kicked a goal, and his first season saw him play 19 games and kick 11 goals for the season.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] He had a vastly improved 2005 season: he played every game, averaged 20 possessions a game and kicked 21 goals.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] He was ranked second for clearances in the Bulldogs team.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] Cooney progressed to the elite of the competition, four seasons after being selected as the number one draft pick.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] Cooney was rewarded for a strong 2008 season by winning the Brownlow Medal.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] He polled 24 votes, beating Brisbane Lions midfielder Simon Black by one vote.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] 1 draft pick (and the first player taken as a priority draft pick) to win the award.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] His 2008 season saw him amass 637 total disposals and boot 23 goals, highlighted by a 25 disposal, 5 goal outing against the Sydney Swans in Round 7.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] He played 25 total games in 2008 and averaged 25.5 disposals per game.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] In 2009, Cooney had another great season, playing 23 games, kicking 14 goals and averaging 26.8 disposals, although he only managed to poll 3 Brownlow Medal Votes.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] He also featured in the official advertisement for the AFL, brushing off several tacklers, including a bull in a bullfighting ring.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] From the 2010–2012 season, Cooney struggled with injury and form, his impact on game, particularly his goal kicking was very minimal, as he only provided 27 majors over 3 seasons, and playing a total of 47 games in that span.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] Cooney then bounced back in 2013, playing 19 games, kicking 19 goals and tallying 485 disposals for the season.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] The 2014 season was Cooney's final year at the Bulldogs, he kicked 13 goals and played 18 games.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] His last game for the Dog's saw him tally 20 disposals and 2 tackles, a game in which the Dog's lost to the GWS Giants.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] In October 2014, Cooney was traded to Essendon.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] The 2015 season was Cooney's first in the red and black, he only managed 11 games and kicked 10 goals, including 3 on debut against the Sydney Swans in Round 1.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] The Essendon Supplements Saga ordeal allowed Adam more of an opportunity to play regular senior football during the 2016 season.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] He managed to play 20 games and kick 6 goals, he also tallied 457 disposals.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] In August 2016, Cooney announced he would retire after the round 22 match against Western Bulldogs at Etihad Stadium.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] His final AFL game was also his 250th game and was fittingly against his old side, the Bulldogs, he gathered 22 disposals and kicked a goal.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] From 2 April 2023, Cooney appeared as a contestant in the ninth season of *I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!*.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] Cooney was eliminated ninth on 27 April 2023.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] Cooney proposed to his partner Haylea McCann with a Burger Ring.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/adam-cooney] On 24 October 2009, he and McCann married in a ceremony at Glenelg Beach, Adelaide.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The **AFL Commission** is the board of directors that governs the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Its chairman has been Richard Goyder since 4 April 2017.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 1985, the AFL (then named Victorian Football League Limited) formed the commission as a body independent of its member clubs, to operate its competition.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 1993, the independent commissioners took over from the AFL's board of directors, who had been representatives of its then-15 member clubs.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the Australian National Football Council which had published the Laws of Australian Football.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL's constitution self-proclaims it to be the "keeper of the code" responsible for the sport of Australian football.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL operates the All-Australian team, World (formerly All-international) team and Australian Football Hall of Fame.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL operates the premier professional Australian Football competition in Australia and the State of Origin competition (1991-1999 and 2026-present).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Since 1998, it has also overseen Australia's involvement in the International Rules Series.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] An independent governing body for the competition was first moved in December 1984 during the fallout of VFL president Allen Aylett's resignation following the South Melbourne Football Club's financially disastrous relocation to Sydney.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The club, managed from Melbourne but playing in Sydney, had sustained substantial finanical losses in Sydney and large loans had been written out by the league to keep them viable, which was also impacting the finances of the competition.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Under its first chief commissioner, Jack Hamilton, the VFL began a restructuring toward a franchise model, whereby member clubs operate licenses owned by the league.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The model helped make private ownership of the Swans possible in 1985, as well as the sale of new licenses, resulting in the entry of the Brisbane Bears and West Coast Eagles in 1987.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Under the new model, many Melbourne clubs struggling for financial viability such as St Kilda, Fitzroy and North Melbourne could be kept afloat by a combination of private ownership and league subsidies from the sale of new clubs and television rights.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The restructuring paved the way for the VFL's expansion into a national competition.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Despite continuing financial troubles at many clubs, including the Swans and Footscray, the AFL was able to turn the competition's finances around by 1989, aided by increased television rights and the sale of $4 million licenses to interstate expansion clubs.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 2014, all AFL players were fully-paid professionals for the first time in the competition's history.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL is governed by its board of directors, called the AFL Commission.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the Australian National Football Council, which ceased operations after 89 years of existence.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 2002, it took over the operations of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 2010, it took over the operations of Women's Football Australia, which ceased operations in 2015.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL took over the operations of the New South Wales Australian Football League Limited, and the AFL subsidiary, AFL NSW/ACT now operates in Australia's most populous eastern state and the ACT.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL promotes and brands the sport under its own name rather than of the formal name of Australian Football.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The ten commissioners are elected by the 18 AFL clubs, with each of the 18 clubs entitled to make nominations, but other Australian Football leagues, associations and clubs do not have any control or representation.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL approves new club franchise licenses to expand its competition.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Since 1987, it has been instrumental in the merger that created the Brisbane Lions, while the Sydney Swans were fully owned by the AFL, which retains a controlling interest and reversion rights in the event the Sydney Swans do not repay debts to the AFL.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL also fully owns the Greater Western Sydney Giants.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Other clubs to have an AFL appointed board include the Sydney Swans, the Gold Coast Suns, Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL operates a Competitive Balance Fund, which redistributes profits to the clubs most in need to help ensure that all of its member clubs are financially sustainable in the long-term.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL is financially dependent on the success of its competitions with the majority of its funding coming from the AFL competition broadcasting rights.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The 2025-2031 rights will earn $4.5 billion, the most lucrative in Australian sporting history.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL operates the Australian Football Hall of Fame, the AFL men's underage championships and AFL Women's underage championships.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] It is also responsible for senior State of Origin competition, which will return in 2026 after a 27-year hiatus.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL is administered by its commission of company directors, which sets policy and has directed the VFL/AFL (known then as the VFL) as the game's most professional league since December 1985.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 1993, the independent commissioners took over as the directors of the AFL from its Board of Directors, which had been appointed as delegates of its then 15 member clubs.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The Board of Directors voted itself out of existence, and the AFL's then 15 member clubs also voted to abolish the old system of club appointment of directors and to adopt a new Memorandum and Articles of Association for the AFL.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] This was a significant change of power: between 1985 and 1993, the VFL/AFL had required explicit approval by a 75% vote of its member teams for major items such as further expansion, mergers, relocations, and major capital works.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the ANFC (see Principle 2 below).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL also created an international policy in 2005 and took over the operations of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Amateur and semi-professional Australian Football competitions across Australia are mostly self-sufficient from the AFL.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] These competitions, their clubs and teams often buy equipment and apparel that is AFL branded which provides revenue to the AFL.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Some junior competitions pay to use the AFL proprietary Auskick program and junior clubs pay the AFL for give-away packs at AFL run promotions in their localities.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL has established a pathway that features junior Academies and scholarships from representational level up to its member clubs.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The highest level is the AFL Academy, with academies for each state being managed by their respective AFL clubs and affiliated governing bodies.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Between 2010 and 2021, the AFL spent between $6–38 million per annum (under 5% of total revenue) on game development grants globally (excluding a one-off COVID-19 Pandemic community football recovery package).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] With a new TV rights deal in 2022 and to help the game at the grassroots continue its recovery post COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased its community grants to $67 million.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The ten commissioners are nominated and elected by vote of the 18 AFL member clubs.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] A two-thirds majority of member clubs have the power to veto over commission decisions.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The commission elects its chairman and employs a chief executive officer to oversees the management and operations of the AFL.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] While the commission is responsible for directing AFL policy, it has, on occasions, become directly involved in on and off-field matters relating to AFL competitions, players, coaches and managers.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] Sometimes these interventions have been in controversial circumstances.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL owns a stake in the Gold Coast and Greater Western Sydney clubs.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The AFL manages a special fund called the Competitive Balance Fund (CBF) since 2004 as a grant of up to $5 million per club to ensure that member clubs remain financially viable.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] The system was later changed to the Annual Special Distribution (ASD) of $6.3 million shared among all clubs, as well as allowing for grants and special concessions, such as payments, to ensure that the AFL member clubs remain viable in the short term.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In 2006, the AFL approved a $2.1 million special financial assistance package for Carlton.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-commission] In early 2009, it increased Melbourne's assistance from $250,000 to $1 million and made a $1 million grant to Port Adelaide.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The **AFL Draft Combine**, formerly known as the **AFL Draft Camp**, is a gathering of prospective talent, where selected potential draftees display their athletic prowess and relevant Australian rules football skills.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Over four days participants are required to undergo a series of medical, psychomotor, athletic and fitness tests as well as interviews conducted by the 18 clubs in the Australian Football League.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The first AFL Draft Camp was held in 1994 at Waverley Park; in 1999 it moved to Canberra, where it was hosted by the Australian Institute of Sport, and in 2011 it was moved to Docklands Stadium.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Each year the Draft Combine is held in the week following the AFL Grand Final.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Through various partnerships the AFL also conducts draft combines around the world with AFL International Combine having been held in Ireland, the United States and New Zealand.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] However unlike the Draft Combine the primary aim of International Combines is to supply secondary talent through the Rookie draft.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The testing results measured at the combine are used to inform recruiters of players' athletic attributes and skills heading into the AFL draft, which is held in November.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Recruiters also have the opportunity to interview participants whom they may potentially want to draft.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Clubs are able to send a representative to the combine, where they are able to conduct a medical screening on participants.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This screening gives clubs an idea of a player's past injuries and future injury concerns.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] To be eligible for the AFL Draft Combine, a player must receive at least 5 nominations from AFL clubs.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Leading into the combine, AFL recruiting managers are expected to submit a list of 70 players from the draft pool whom they would like to screen at the national combine.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Approximately 100 invitees attend the draft combine.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Draft hopefuls who don't receive enough nominations for the national combine but still receive 3 or 4 nominations have the opportunity to attend their respective state screening.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Players who are overlooked for the national combine may be invited to attend a state-based combine, where similar testing is done.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The following tests performed at the combine are associated with the attributes required to perform in the AFL.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Players are to finish a 20-metre leg before the sound of the beep; they continue to run back and forth as the time in between each beep gets shorter.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The test starts at level 1 and finishes at level 21.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] When a person fails to make the line before the beep, they no longer are allowed to continue.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This test was replaced with the yo-yo test in 2017.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] In groups of 10–20, players are to complete a 3000-metre run as fast as they can.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This was replaced by the 2 km time trial in 2017.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This test is designed to measure both speed and endurance.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Here players complete six 30-metre sprints, with the cumulative time recorded.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The player starts standing upright; once they pass through the gates, the player is to navigate around a series of poles (without touching them or knocking them down) and reach the finishing gates as quickly as possible.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The individual being tested begins in a crouched position.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] They are then to sprint as fast as they can up to 20 metres.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Sensors are used to measure the time taken to the 5m, 10m and 20m mark.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Each player is given 3 attempts at this, with the quickest time being recorded.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This test measures a player's vertical while jumping off one leg from a running start.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] It uses a 'Vertec' device to measure their vertical reach while in the air.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This is similar to the running vertical jump; however, the player instead takes off on two feet from a stationary start.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The aim again is to hit the fingers as high up as possible on the Vertec.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This test was devised by Nathan Buckley and is used to measure a player's kicking efficiency over six kicks.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Six targets are set out at distances of 20, 30 and 40 metres.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] An official is designated to request a target at random and call the instructions out to the kicker.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The kicker then proceeds hit the target.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Each kick is given a score from one to five (five being the perfect kick).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Matthew Lloyd designed this test to measure how well a player takes possession of a football and is able to dispose of it using a handball.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Three targets are set up on both the left and right sides at distances of 6, 8 and 10 metres.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The test starts with an official either rolling or throwing a football at the player; an instruction of what target to hit is then called out by the official.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The player then attempts to handball the ball at the target.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This is done six times, and a score from one to five is allocated for each handball.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This test was constructed by Brad Johnson and measures a player's accuracy kicking for goal.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] This test takes place on an oval with four markers placed at different angles and distances to kick from.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Five kicks are taken in total: two set shots, two snaps (one left and one right) and one kick on the run.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] A score is then derived from the number of goals and behinds a player kicks.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Measurements of a player's height, weight, skinfolds, arm length and hand span are all recorded.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The fastest agility test ever recorded at any AFL combine was 7.761 seconds by Tyrone Thorne at the 2019 Western Australia draft combine.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Since the 2000s, the AFL began to look to increasingly recruit athletic talent from outside Australia.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] It is estimated over 100,000 people participate in the sport outside Australia and the Australian Football International Cup takes place every three years in Melbourne, where teams from 18 countries compete against each other.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] With the exception of international rookies, the AFL however has traditionally looked outside of its grassroots player base for amateur and professional athletes from other sports with transferrable skills.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] As such this is the primary aim of the International Combines.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] All AFL international combines have been indefinitely postponed since the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The US AFL Combine was held annually between 2012 and 2017.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The first combine was run in 2012, and it has been run semi-annually since 2017.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Each year, a minimum of two of the group were chosen to partake in the AFL National Combine held in Melbourne.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] From 2015, the AFL shifted its focus exclusively to rucks; and, as such, all 15 participants from the 2015 combine were from a college basketball background.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] After a poor yield between 2015 and 2017 while scouting for American athletes over 2 metres tall, the AFL put the program on hold to focus on talent in Ireland and New Zealand.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The European Combine has been held annually since 2010 and overseen by the AFL.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Since 2015, it has been run by International Talent Manager Tadhg Kennelly, a former player for the Sydney Swans who was originally drafted from Ireland.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] All of the early trials were held in Dublin.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Among those who try out, a large proportion are Gaelic footballers, as the skill set of Gaelic football is considered similar to that of AFL.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Unlike the key positions sought from US and New Zealand athletes, AFL clubs are typically searching Ireland's gaelic talent for running midfielders and attacking (rebound) defenders.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The two best-performing participants at the combine are then given the opportunity to attend the AFL National Combine.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] To date, only a couple of the tested players have been successful at AFL level, with the majority of successful Irish players scouted by other means.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] During a drought in combine talent, former Irish player Pearce Hanley in 2016 was critical of the format as a recruiting method due to its primary focus on athletic testing over game adaptability.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Others did not sign at the event but decided to sign sometime later, as was the case of Darragh Joyce.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] In 2019, a women's combine was run for the first time as part of a pathway to the AFL Women's competition.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] In 2022, the AFL flagged a return of the European Combine; however, it did not oversee them in 2023, with independent recruiters holding trials in Ireland instead.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The first New Zealand combine was held in 2013.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Unlike the combines in the US and Europe, New Zealand's combine targets mainly junior (under-18s) rugby and soccer players with key-position potential.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] Kurt Heatherley was signed by Hawthorn via the AFL Combine in Melbourne in 2012 before the New Zealand combines had begun.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-international-combine] The first women's combine was held in 2014.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] AFL New Zealand currently has 30,000 Registered Players, although this is refuted, as it would mean that each of the clubs in the country has 1,875 players per team.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] Australian rules football is a sport played in New Zealand rapidly gaining popularity.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] AFL New Zealand co-ordinate the national team, who have competed in the Australian Football International Cup and crowned international champions in 2005.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] Since 2012 the national side has played against the National Australian Under 17 team (NAB AFL Academy).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] The first game was won convincingly by the AFL Academy by 91 points.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] 2013 saw the Australians win by 44 points and in 2014 it took a goal in the final minutes to win their third straight game by only 4 points.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] NZAFL selects a team of the best Australian-based players with NZ heritage.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] This team includes some AFL legends including Simon Black (Brisbane Lions AFL) and Wayne Schwass – (Sydney Swans AFL).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] The AFLNZ National Provincial Championships were an annual tournament between the regional leagues comprising the New Zealand Australian Football League.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] The first of the current incarnation of the NPC was held on 25 and 26 September 2004 in Christchurch.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] Since 2016 AFL New Zealand runs a 4 team 8 round men's national competition as part of its high performance programme similar to the AFL Academy club pathway in Australia.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] Players are recruited via a national draft from throughout the country.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] Matches are played at North Harbour Stadium outer oval in Auckland and QE2 Park Christchurch.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/afl-new-zealand] A women's national league was established in 2019, with only Waitākere having a full women's roster, an opponent, the Lions was drafted from female players across the country.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Australia has named a senior Australian rules football team, known as the All-Australian team since 1947.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] This team, however has never officially played an international Australian rules football match.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] This is primarily because the sport is played professionally in Australia.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] It has previously sent teams to play against Ireland's amateur Gaelic Athletic Association in the hybrid code of International Rules Football as the Australia international rules football team (this article is not about that team).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] While the All-Australian team does not compete, the **AFL National Academy** (known simply as the "AFL Academy") is a national team composed of underage (under-19) players.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In the past it has played annual matches against New Zealand, though currently it competes only against semi-professional state league teams.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] History has shown that more than two thirds of Academy players go on to professional careers at senior level in the Australian Football League.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In addition, sides representing Indigenous Australia have competed internationally, including the Indigenous All-Stars against Papua New Guinea and the Flying Boomerangs.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Australia remains undefeated, although Papua New Guinea came within two goals of a historic win at Football Park in 1978 and New Zealand within a goal at Wellington Stadium in 2014.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Early in the spread of football codes across the globe, international tours and tests played a pivotal role.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] However, from the sport's early days, although plans were tabled for tours to England, various leagues had lacked the resources and organisation to send tours overseas.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] H C A Harrison "Father of Australian Football" was a supporter of the idea of international matches against England and New Zealand, and in London in 1884, pitched playing under compromise rules, however the idea was rejected.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The idea was made more difficult as prior to the Federation of Australia the Australian colonies could still not reach a consensus on the idea of fielding a national side.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Some teams did however tour and played matches in Australia against Australian sides, notably in 1888 and 1889, the British & Irish Lions and New Zealand Native team played matches against clubs in Australia but no recognised international tests.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] These tours were conditional on Australian leagues playing some matches under rugby rules to keep the competition fair.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Generally games were won by the teams playing their own code and this led to the perception that the codes were by now too dissimilar for such matches to continue.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Unlike the football codes with less players sending squads of 18 to 22 players on international tours would prove to be an expensive exercise and sharing the costs across multiple colonies would prove much more difficult than, for example, New South Wales sending a national rugby team.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] It wasn't until the formation of the national body, the Australasian Football Council in 1906 that the opportunity presented itself for funding and organisation for a national team.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] However representatives of the two strongest leagues, the Victorian Football League and South Australian Football League, in an effort to protect their primacy in Australia, lobbied the council to form a strict policy discouraging the game from being played overseas.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Through the council they allocated all funds to interstate representation, and none to international representation.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The policy was boosted by a wave of post-Federation Australian nationalism.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In 1906 the council's official policy became "one flag, one destiny, one football game" and chose to play all matches under an Australian flag, on Australian turf with an Australian manufactured ball.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The first request for international tour came in 1906 from Australian rules football in South Africa, the AFC therefore replied that if it wanted to play against Australia, it would have to send a team to Australia.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] This was to become the council's default stance.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] New Zealand had only one representative on the council, and faced opposition from most of the Australian colonies.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Though it was given permission to send a side to the 1908 Melbourne Carnival (which defeated Queensland and New South Wales) the AFC never fielded a national team against them.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Subsequent calls from overseas for Australia to send teams to the United States (1909), New Zealand (1910), Japan (1910) and Canada (1912) were all rejected by the AFC.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] For a country with less than a thousand players, USA's junior athletes proved highly competitive against the Australian sides.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In 1912, Canada sent a junior touring side to Australia, however the tour was not recognised by the AFC and as such no composite Australian representative side was fielded against them.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] With the rapid growth in the United States, the AFC's delegate from Western Australia strongly argued for sanctioned tours to both the United States and Canada, however the governing body elected not to.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The result was that most competitions outside Australia went into permanent recess by the end of the 1920s.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In contrast, the top leagues in Australia were going professional and a widening gap in interstate representative matches would make it almost impossible for other countries to compete.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] A promotional tour, known as the Australian Football World Tour, took place in 1967, with matches played in Ireland, the United Kingdom, and the United States, though without any local players no international matches of Australian rules were played.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] This resulted in the first International Rules matches played between Australia and a touring County Meath Gaelic football team, Meath being the reigning All-Ireland senior football champions.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The national side was known as the "Galahs".
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Ireland would maintain the VFL's primary international focus (especially given its ongoing Irish Experiment recruiting initiative) through to the 21st century.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Though it was not officially endorsed by the AFC, support for the idea was continued by the VFL/AFL and later Australian Amateur Football Council.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In the 1960s and 1970s, Australian rules was unexpectedly booming in the Pacific in Papua New Guinea and Nauru.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] While Nauru had been soundly defeated by PNG it was considered far too small a nation to field a competitive side against Australia.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Papua New Guinea however with tens of thousands of players to draw from, had a fast moving and hard hitting side that was competitive against some of the VFL's strongest clubs, and was extremely determined to compete against Australia.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In 1977 a Victorian U17 team travelled to Port Moresby and were almost defeated.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] PNG persevered and in 1978 sent a team to Adelaide, and in a historic match came close to beating Australia.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] However the Australian National Football Council withdrew its promise to admit PNG as a voting member, along with senior funding and plans to tour Papua New Guinea and the local competitions soon collapsed.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] This was in part due to the country's national sporting body withdrawing funding due to a lack of international competition.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In turn this also left Australia with no opponent.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] When the International Australian Football Council was formed in 1995 one of its aims was to 'establish and promote an official World Cup of Australian Football'.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The initial proposal was for similar eligibility criteria to other football codes which would mean that it could draw the significant pool of Australians born overseas or with a parent or grandparent from the country they chose to represent.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] This would in turn reduce the logistical and financial burden on overseas clubs who would send their best players to top up the squads.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] At the time it was thought that 2008, being the 150th anniversary of the game, was the appropriate date.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The idea of Australia eventually entering an amateur side was first proposed.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In 1999 a proposal was received from the New Zealand Australian Football League (NZAFL), suggesting that the World Cup be brought forward to 2002.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] An approach was then made to the national body, the AFL, asking for their support in staging the event.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The AFL agreed on the basis that the event was renamed the "International Cup", that an Australian side would not compete and that there be strict eligibility criteria to exclude Australian players.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In 2004, the AFL formed its own International Policy, pushed for the dissolution of the IAFC to became formally recognised as the world governing body for the sport.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] It took the International Cup over and put it under its development arm.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The idea of an Australian team, even a development or amateur one, participating in the tournament was dismissed.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Australia did not compete internationally at any recognised level until the AFL Commission in 1998 formed a 10-year partnership with the Australian Sports Commission (ASC) and the Australian Institute of Sport (AIS), the AIS-AFL Academy, with national sports funding.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The AIS junior development funding was contingent on international competition, which the AFL was able to satisfy through a junior International Rules Series against Ireland.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The AIS funded scholarships to 30 17 year old players for a year based on their football performance as a 16 year old, their positive attitude to education and schooling and potential to play at professional AFL level.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] However, with the GAA cancelling both the senior and junior series in 2006, the AFL had to find another opponent in order to continue to receive national sports funding. which it sought to capitalise on burgeoning Australian investment in Australian rules football in South Africa.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Following some highly unevenly matched contests, the gap between the two countries drew comments from AFL CEO Andrew Demetriou the South Africans would be better suited to playing a game with a round ball (referring to International Rules but possibly also soccer).
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] In 2011, the program expanded to include two squads however the AFL abandoned the South African program and sent a side on tour to Europe to play against a combined side.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The Australian Institute of Sport withdrew from the partnership in 2013 to focus on Olympics recognised sports.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The National Australia Bank extended its Australian Football sponsorship to the AFL Academy to fill the gap left by the AIS.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The AFL's partnership in New Zealand with Wellington Regional Stadium helped fill the gap left by the AIS and it began playing its development team against an open aged NZ sides in 2012.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Competing as the AFL Academy (or Australia U17) an annual series of tours was established against New Zealand as part of a junior development pathway with AFL New Zealand.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The AFL also sent tours to Europe in 2013 and 2014 to compete against a combined AFL Europe side known as the European Legion.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The AFL also set up International Combines in Europe and New Zealand from which some of the athletes participated as the Academy's opposition.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] New Zealand matches were later extended to include women's matches however COVID-19 pandemic put international matches on hold.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] At the end of 2018, the AFL put an end to overseas tours for its AFL Academy, which meant that international sides would once again require to travel to Australia to compete.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Unable to secure nationals sports funding the AFL also restructured the AFL Academy into state-based academies, diverting funding intended for overseas tours into academies featuring its clubs in developing states of New South Wales and Queensland.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Since 2019 the state-based academies have formed the basis of the AFL National Academy teams for boys and girls, made up of primarily players in the under-18 age bracket.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] The boys team have played once-a-year fixtures against teams from the Victorian Football League and South Australian National Football League, while the girls have competed against combined under-23 state teams.
[src:australia-national-australian-rules-football-team/australia-national-australian-rules-football-team] Both teams undertake regular training and high-development camps, as well as partake in yearly formal matches against opposition.
